If you did not already have a combination padlock you would not know how to set it. It is a good padlock which you can't beat for the cost. It was shipped promptly.

I received the lock very quickly and it looks secure for it's size.  However, it came in an envelope without any instructions on how to change the combination.  The product description does say it can be changed as often as you like, so it would be nice to know how to do that!  If they would have enclosed that little instruction paper I would have given them 4 stars. If the spring was stronger I would have given them 5 stars.

Ok, figured it out. Was no place to insert a pin (or key) to reset the combination like I've seen on other combination padlocks.  But the "pin" on this lock is part of the shackle, the curved part that pushes into the case. You can see the little knob of metal (the pin)on the shackle when it's unlocked, it's hidden when locked and the shackle is pushed into the case.

 I made you some instructions for changing the combination:
1) With it unlocked, hold the lock upright with the numbers facing you. Instead of inserting the shackle back into the case, rotate it 90 degrees to the left and push it down.  The little knob of metal on the shackle will fit into a second slot in the case at that 90 degree position.

2) While still pushing the shackle down into the case, turn the 3 dials to the new desired combination.

3) After the dials are on the new combination, stop pushing the shackle down, being careful to not disturb the three dials on your new combination.  Turn the shackle back to the normal position to lock it.

4) Now push the shackle down to lock it and spin the combination dials while it's pushed down.  It is now locked and the new combination is saved.

I changed it several times and verified that the old combinations no longer worked.  The spring isn't very strong and you don't have to push down very hard.

reviewText:
I bought this for my almost 4 years old daughter who happens to love the color purple and hearts. This bangle fit what she wants well and it didn't disappointed. My daughter's face lit up when she opened this particular gift yesterday and has been wearing the bracelet since then.  I paired it with the hoop earrings to make it a set which I deemed too big for her age, I'm hoping she will wear them someday.

The bracelet has a great, precision design - there's nothing sloppy on this bangle. The color is just as pictured, it looks expensive and has a substantial weight to it.  FYI, bangle is oblongish and not round to better fit wrist. It's not too small nor too big for a barely 4 years old.

I bought 3 of these enamel hinged bracelets for my young nieces, ages 6, 8 and 11.  The parents and grandparents do most of the heavy lifting when it comes to gifts, so what's an aunt on a budget to do?  In addition, my nieces are blessed with a "high quality lifestyle", so that often rules out most inexpensive toys.  I needed a very specific type of jewelry piece, but I also needed to keep it age and occasion appropriate.  These bracelets fit the bill perfectly!

The weight and feel of the piece is good, substantial.  It feels sturdy with a bit of heft to it.  The metal is 18k gold over sterling silver and looks good.  The gold and enamel detailing throughout the design is clean with no sloppy flaws that I could see.  The inside of the bracelet is gold with heart cut outs lining the full circumference of the bracelet.  The box clasp has a "tongue" end that fits into a box chamber on the other end and fastenes with two gold clasps on each side that snap down over a little ball-like fixture.  It's sturdy and I don't worry that it will fall off.  At the same time, it's slim and inconspicuous.

The oval shape of the bracelet ensures it will sit nicely on a small wrist.  The width and height of the design is about 1/8 inch.  The diameter of the bracelet measures 2 1/8 inches horizontally, measuring from the inside of the left side to the inside of the right and 1 3/4 inch from top to bottom.  The overall size and appearance of the design is substantial but not too heavy or bulky.

The designs are also very age and occasion appropriate.  The colors are bright and designs cute but there's no cheese factor.  The style is appealing while also being very refined.  They would be perfect for any occasion.  The nice quality doesn't work against it.  Some pieces I found seemed too "keepsake" -like but these have a really special quality to them without being too special, if that makes any sense.  And at this price, I'm actually quite stunned and pleasantly surprised.  This is a great value.

Overall, a really beautiful piece that's appropriate for young girls, really nice quality and an amazing price.  These have saved "cool Aunt Mimi" this Christmas!  I highly recommend these!!

reviewText:
There is so much in change that Seiko has really been putting their energy in their timepieces for their Pulsar line. Not only with the simplistic style, but by placing some of the classic movements that Seiko had been known for with years in their timepieces like having new solar watches that have been met with both classic and simplistic style, but also in value. They have been very strong in moves, because people have been deeply overlooking their Pulsar watches in favor of Seiko's mainstream line. That also has been said with their automatic quartz watches from the Seiko Kinetic line, which have been deeply under-recognized in the classic horologists eyes in movement and price. This silver-tone piece from Pulsar is a nice looking classic watch in value, has good water resistance and easy to setup time. But that is really it. It really gets its energy by the movement of the wrist, like a automatic watch to charge the battery. Yet, there could've been more for the value of the piece like better illuminated hands to see the watch's time in the dark, and a easier to see date window. Overall, this still is a classic watch that Seiko has shown for their Pulsar line, but honestly with their new Solar watches, I would honestly consider passing this one up.

The sole seemed perfectly contoured to my foot. No blisters, no hot spots, nothing. I would recommend wearing a thick hiking sock, as the soles are relatively hard, but not uncomfortable. If you have wide feet, and feel like typical hiking boots pinch the outside of your foot, these would be perfect for you. Highly recommended!

From the first day I put these on, they were comfortable.  They are lightweight, not too hot, and flexible, allowing me to run or walk when working my dog, and yet they provide plenty of support.  I have flat feet, so I appreciated the absence of an arch support, which often feels like a rock in my shoe.  Yet the construction of the boot or last seems to keep me from pronating, and I am able to cover distances without taxing my joints.  My activity requires agility and these boots fit the bill. I would give them ten stars if I could.

I purchased this item as an Eid gift for a man.  It has masculine lines and was exactly what I had in mind.  I remained cautiously optimistic about what I'd get for a couple of reasons:

1.  The product description doesn't list dimensions.  Photos are deceptive (as we all know).
As I awaited delivery I decided if I got:

The size of a Kennedy $0.50 piece=Ideal.
The size of a quarter=Most likely, so okay.
The size of a nickel=Underwhelming.

Result:  Ideal.

2.  Craftsmanship:  Again, hard to gauge based on a photo.  At the $30 price point, I was skeptical. But I liked the fact it was described to be stainless steel, a non-precious metal which is appropriate for Muslim men to wear.

Result:  Exceeds expectation.

Why? The calligraphic script is lovely, and appears to be durable and not cheaply painted (I.e. durable to wear). The "swivel" design (think globe) is a nice touch which is very distinctive in design.  Finally, the caliph, "M'ashaAllah" graces one side of the "coin" and the other side displays the jeweler logo.  But has ample room to have an inscription engraved.

3.  Deliverable:  Being end of Ramadan, I was skeptical of getting the item in time, although it was listed as "in stock".

Result:  Amazon delivers, when they say they will.

Conclusion:  Buy with confidence.

I have two of these. Very pleased. Adapters for nearly every make and model Laptop. The removable, inline USB Charging port is very handy and free's up a USB port on the laptop (it is for Charging only, it isn't a USB data port)

It has the power to run the laptop and charge simultaneously (some emergency chargers can't do both)

Has performed flawlessly and the two pronged plug actually prevents buzzing from ground loops if you plug into amplifiers or auxiliary sound systems (although it also means you're not grounded)

A great charger/powersupply at a reasonable price.

I just received this charger and, after reading other reviews have some of the same comments.
It is a bulk product, not one that comes in 'official' Targus packaging.  All the parts were the same and the charger, cables and tips all looked new but there were not instructions included and the 'handy carry bag' was an inexpensive cloth bag.  Fortunately I have several cases, bags, etc. that will work for this charger all of which are better quality.  Since it was not mentioned in the information for the product, I've knocked 2 stars off the rating.
I did not have a problem with identifying which tip was which, the embossing was clear to me.  I looked at this charger at Staples and saw which tip was used for my ASUS laptop but I doublechecked on the Targus website.
I too don't care much for the USB dongle but it was not difficult to put on and I'll leave it on.
I took a volt meter and measured the output voltage with the correct ASUS tip and found it was 19.5 volts, just as advertised so I'm not expecting any problems with overcharging.  The ASUS model I have #X53E# stops charging at 95% anyway.
When assembled the cables are longer than the ASUS OEM charger and this will be handy for travelling.  I'll use the OEM charger for home so I don't have to remove it.  Besides, having a spare is a good idea, as far as I'm concerned.
summary: Seems to be worth the money.

Then she tried the holder on her woven-fabric jacket and while it stayed put for awhile, when she took the jacket off the sunglasses came off too.  She's hesitant to make two pin holes in her favorite black leather jacket, but she thinks the big sunglasses would probably stay put.  Even if they don't, she likes the design and utility of the pin.  She occasionally has to take her prescription glasses off to read labels and tags, and this pin would give her a good place to temporarily put her glasses when shopping or browsing.  She usually tried putting them on top of her head or in the brim of her favorite fedora, but the glasses always slid off quickly, so this pin definitely solves one problem for her.  Maybe there could be a version of this pin that would work with the big "fit-overs" as well, with a wider east-west oval instead of a round loop under the cross pin.

First off, they absolutely are NOT COSTUME BOOTS. I almost had a heart attack when I read another user make that claim. No where on ANY site does it state that they're costume boots. Not even on Demonia's official site. Please disregard that user's statement. Demonia doesn't make costume boots. They are real, rugged, sturdy, heavy, STEEL TOE, every day boots; however, I don't think anyone could wear them all day because they're not exactly comfort boots. I predict about 2-3 hours, unless you manage to break them in. But..look at them. They look like fortified tanks on your feet. Would you expect to be comfortable riding across country in a tank? No. So, don't expect to walk across country in these. But, what you -can expect- is what you see-- a pair of massive, amazing, study pieces of art that will not only impress you, but everywhere who sees you in them.

Also, they are exactly as described, aside from the fact that they didn't list steel toe when the absolutely are. Personally, I love steel toes. Protects your feet in mosh pits. Unfortunately for me, I have to return them because I took a chance with size 8, but I definitely need a 9 in these so I'm going to buy a slightly different style, but exactly the same kind of boot.

I bought this for my dad this year as a Father's Day gift. He isn't a super-nerdy Trekkie but he laughed about it just the same. I mean, check out Shatner's face! Is there anything more over-the-top? And I mean that in the best sense! Anyone who's seen "The Wrath of Khan" or is a Shatner fan will appreciate the humor behind this. Getting them to wear the shirt is another story, though. Even if they don't wear it outside of the house(my dad is a distinguished 59), they'll get a good laugh. I washed the shirt before gifting it so that it was nice and soft. I didn't have any trouble with the paint cracking, as others have mentioned, and it's not some cheesy iron-on transfer, either. This is a good quality screen-printed image that should last a long time provided you wash the shirt inside-out on cold and don't dry it on high heat. I am very pleased with this purchase.

He evens uses it as a regular beanie when it's not too cold by folding the ear band both when running and just for lounging around. I highly recommend this beanie if you know the right size to get.

I bought this hat with high hopes, however it is ridiculously tight and even after wearing it several times it never loosened or relaxed. I suppose if I had hair it would have stayed in place better, but despite being very tight it would not stay in place and kept moving down into my eyes.

i have used this hat for over three years and generally it functions well.  the windproof headband works as advertised (i've run down to a windy -5F with this hat on top of a thin balaclava) and my head and ears have never been too cold.  that being said, the hat has been shelved due to the headband constantly wanting to fall over my eyes-similar to the review above.  i have an average/above-average size adult male head and i own the l/xl size and other than the headband falling over my eyes, the hat works very well.

I had to return this hat, because it was just too tight for me, it was very uncomfortable(I bought the L/XL size). I would say i have an average sized head, when pulled down all the way, it covers the ears which is nice, because it would keep your ears warm.  That portion of the hat is not overly thick, but makes it somewhat difficult to hear, which i didn't like.  Also, when pulled down all the way, it came down too far on my forehead, and almost covered my eyes.  But if you don't pull it down that far, it just doesn't feel right.  Maybe it's made for a different size head.  I'm going to try something else.

reviewText:
I purchased the Born Asbee Riding Boots in the Brick Red color, which actually looks more like a slightly reddish Cognac brown.  The Brick Red works very well with black, brown, tan, and olive bottoms, and goes very well with denim.
I followed recommendations from reviews that I read stating to order 1/2 size down.  I usually am right between an 8.5M and 9M (39EU), and ordered the size 8.  The size 8 fit very well with light- to mid-weight socks.  The heels do not slip and there is plenty of room for toes to be comfortable, but not excess room.  The insole is contoured (arch support) and well padded.  There is a small heel (1.5") which allows these to be walk-all-day in comfort boots.  I get compliments on them every time I wear them. They have enough room for wearing over slim leg jeans, but also look OK (not too roomy) with tights and a skirt.  The full inside zip makes them easy to put on and to wear over jeans/leggings.  The shaft height is 15.5" tall and the circumference at the widest point is also 15.5".
I would love to get another color, but they are sold out everywhere that I look.  The only place that I see them is on that eb.y auction site.
They are well worth the full price for the beautiful quality Italian leather and sturdy construction.  They will be go-to's in my closet for years to come.
summary: Best Pair of Boots That I Own!

reviewText:
After having my other pair of black thick-heel pumps destroyed a year ago, I was searching for a similar pair when I stumbled on these. They look FANTASTIC! The picture doesn't do them justice. They look a little squished and clunky if the photo, but they are very elegant on your feet. I usually have trouble walking in bevel-toe heels, but these are not quite so beveled as other platforms, and are very comfortable. Fits true to size, with just a little extra room in the heel, which helps against blisters.

The only con I have found does involved that little extra room though. The vamp (the material on the sides) and the toe box only allow for the smallest no-see socks. If you want to wear hose or tights with these, I would suggest buying a non-slip front foot (ball) pad insert as your foot may slide a little forward while walking because the insert in these are rather slick. I haven't experienced walking out of this shoe yet, but I think if your foot got a little sweaty, it may be possible if you don't have something on the inside.

Boy... Where do I start?

I purchased these shoes in the summer, and I've only worn them ONCE. Understanding that they are a primarily indoor basketball shoe, outdoors will be pure HELL. I made the mistake of wearing them once on a outdoors court, and will never do it again. The shoe seems to fit when you first try them on, but the inside sole of the shoe is built with a weird hard material around the toes (not to mention that it's also pointy on the toes), which makes it hard to run up and down the court because your feet are constantly rubbing on the hard inner sole, causing blisters. I remember wearing them for 2 games and immediately taking them off to play in my Vans. My Vans are more comfortable than wearing these Nikes, which is sad. I like the ankle support in these shoes, but the inner sole kills the whole idea of wearing these shoes for me.

However, the seller of these shoes was very fast on shipping, and had no problems during the buying/shipping process. Product was in great shape (completely new shoes).

With that being said, I do not recommend these shoes at all.

Im in love. This dress is so stylish and cute!
Im 53, 117 lbs, 34DD, 36-27-36 and I ordered a size S based on the sellers size chart. It fits beautifully, so for me the size chart was accurate.
Its made from a very lightweight knit fabric thats also very soft. I would say its comparable to t-shirt fabric. The kind of t-shirt that has some nice drape to it, not the heavy thick cotton kind. As a result the dress is very comfortable. I love being able to wear a dress and still feel comfortable.
The belt is cute, but its really long. I didn't like the way it was hanging past my knees, so I did some kind of wrap around thing that shortened it. Because the braided belt has a messy look at the ends, it worked without making it look too strange. Perhaps its because I did this additional wrap-around, but I didn't have any problems with the belt coming untied as other reviewers mentioned. Or perhaps its because I had read about that before I ever wore the dress so I knew to tie it firmly. In any case, my belt stayed tied throughout the entire workday without any need for adjustment.
I was so taken with how cute this dress was when I received it that I totally forgot to check over the seams to identify if its well made. But I wore it to work all day and didn't notice any issues while doing so.
I got several complements (that weren't from my mom, lol) on this dress when I wore it, and I always feel like thats the best way to tell when something looks good on you.
To sum it up, sizing is accurate if you use the size chart, the fabric is soft and stretchy, and it looks good. Nuff said!

I bought this to use with a chain. I punctured a hole in the corner to clip to it and so far it's worked well and holding up since it's real leather.

I originally had a chained leather wallet for 15 years before it wore out. I replaced it with several $10-25 wallets, a few from "novelty" type stores as they often sell wallets with chains, but most never lasted more than 2-3 months before ripping or losing stitches (my chain is heavy and my nephew/niece like to pull and hang on it). I bought this wallet as it was the same price on Amazon as the fake leather wallets (despite $40 retail sticker on the box) and so far it's better than expected. I'll update in a few months to see how the hole holds up.

Based on the picture of the dry Fluorite, I wouldn't have chosen this product for my project.  I purchased this based on the picture provided by the seller showing the color after being mixed in (presumably resin).
If you are wanting a deeper purple color, do not purchase this.  Your finished product after being sealed in resin will be very close in shade to the picture of the dry product and more pink in color.  Keep in mind that this is a granulated gem; so if you're looking for something that will actually dissolve in the resin, this is not it.  Also, pouring resin over this did not seem to work; the resin just sat on top of the granules.  Maybe if I had waited long enough, it would have eventually seeped in.  Trust me on this part; mix in a separate container, before pouring it in your mold.  Do not stir this up in your plastic mold; it will scratch it up, ruin your mold, and leave you with an ugly cloudy finish on your piece!

reviewText: Gorgeous watch, great movement.  Pictures don't do it justice.  It's a nice in-house movement and a limited edition watch that will only have 800 in the world.  If you're a starting collector or want something different than everyone else, this is for you.

I bought this watch directly from Sea-Gull's US distributor, where it is slightly cheaper. As to the watch itself...

While I could compare the Dragon King to something like the Orient Mako, I believe Sea-Gull is aiming higher with this model. This watch has a sapphire crystal and a hacking, hand winding, 28,800 bph movement cloned from the ETA 2824 - the Sea-Gull ST-21 in Sea-Gull's top grade, AAA. As such, I'll provide some comparisons to my Baume & Mercier 8779 and the Edox C1, both of which use an ETA 2824 movement. The B&M cost me around $900, although it is currently selling for more.  I got the Edox as a gift for a relative on a daily deal site for $270, but it regularly sells for around $450.

The DK comes in a very solid cardboard box with a Chinese dragon in gold on it. Inside, the watch rests on a pillow inside a cardboard separator. I would say the box is a bit nicer than the typical Seiko box, not at the same level as the typical Swiss box. The watch shares the box with a unique warranty card featuring an embossed dragon, the invoice, and a truly awful instruction manual translated by someone who didn't speak much English. "Automatic mechanic watch that is winded by swing rotor, so regular exercise (Don 't designedly), and wearing the watch at lest 8HS every day." Interestingly, although the watch is called "SEA-GULL" on its dial, it is called "Seagull" in the manual. The watch was very securely wrapped in plastic inside the box.

This is a large watch, by my standards, at 43mm. The lugs are well contoured and it fits me very well. The bracelet is one of the most comfortable I've encountered, despite a lack of half links. Seagull attempts to make up for that with micro-adjustments on the clasp, but there is only one adjustment point. So if you don't get lucky with the length of the links, you could be in trouble. The links also feature push pins rather than the B&M and Edox's screw pins, not surprising at this price point. They were fairly easily removed, however. The bracelet also has an attractive combination of brushed and polished metal - polished on the outside, brushed in the middle, but with a sunken, polished strip down the center. The clasp is a very solid single fold with a double push button action. Other than the lack of half-links and screw pins, I would consider the bracelet to be at least as good as the B&M's, and I certainly like the clasp better than my Ulysse Nardin's. The clasp has "SEA-GULL" engraved on it. After months of use, I still find it very comfortable despite its size and weight.

The case is brushed, with a consistent finish, and feels very solid. The crown is polished, screw-down and has an embossed "S." It is protected by a conventional crown guard. The action is firm - not as solid as the B&M, but the overall design is probably a bit better than the Edox. The bezel is a very typical Rolex Submariner homage, nowhere near as interesting as the B&M's dodecagonal model. It's not quite a literal Sub (the 0-15 scale is not marked differently from the other indices) but it's pretty close, down to the scalloping. The 120-click bezel does not quite align properly with the dial - one of the two flaws that keep this watch from quite matching its Swiss competitors.

The dial itself is matte black with SEA-GULL / Automatic / Dragon King / 200M printed in white. It somewhat resembles an Omega Seamaster.  A number of different fonts are used, but it works pretty well. There is also a blue chapter ring with minute indices and 5-minute numeric indicators, with an orange "60" at twelve o'clock. The printing is crisp, not quite at B&M levels but perhaps slightly better than Edox. Indices are applied, simple lozenges with large bits of white lume painted on. The indices are not as refined as the B&M or Edox, and on a couple of them the lume is not quite centered. You can't see that with the naked eye but it's visible with a 10x loupe. Again, quality is probably comparable to Edox, not at B&M levels. The hour and minute hands are standard batons, heavily lumed. The second hand is a little more interesting, with a large counterweight and two lumed dots towards the end. The second hand reaches the end of the indices, the minute hand the mid-point. The hour hand doesn't quite reach the indices.

Speaking of the lume, Kevin Ma (Sea-Gull's US dealer, and a real pleasure to deal with) admitted on the WUS forum that it wasn't up to Seiko levels. That's definitely true. And it's not even close to the B&M's league. This is not for lack of lumed material, which is abundant - the quality of the lume just isn't there.

The back of the watch features an engraved Chinese dragon that looks great, and, along with some other text, an indication that this is #23 of 800. I doubt a limited edition Sea-Gull is all that collectible - I suspect Sea-Gull will have a Dragon King II when this edition runs out, which may be better.

It seems to have settled at about +12 seconds per day, pretty comparable to the B&M.  What remains to be seen is the durability of the black anodization on the bezel. The B&M really shines there - despite being one of my more abused watches, there isn't a scratch in that anodization, whereas my wife's Orient sub homage is all scratched up despite much less wear. I will report back after further use of the Sea-Gull - after a couple of months of light use, it's still looking good.

Finally, and disappointingly, unlike other Sea-Gulls this one does not say "China Made" anywhere on it. I think I know why they did that, but it's disappointing that they won't advertise the national origin of their new "flagship."

This is a watch that is almost fully competitive with brands like Hamilton for a significantly lower price. I struggled with the question of four vs. five stars - it is a great value for the money. So why did I settle on four?  Because it's intended to be a dive watch, and the slightly mis-aligned bezel and inferior lume detract from that intended function.  If they improve the alignment of the bezel and the lume on the next edition, this watch will be an easy five star watch, fully competitive with a good, basic Swiss automatic, at a substantially lower price.
summary: Excellent watch for the price - a couple of flaws

reviewText: I bought this because I love how comfortable Hue's leggings are (for travel, etc) but I hate how I look in skinny jeans.  It is really very nice.  It looks just like jeans (with pockets) and even feels like jeans (just thinner).  Only negatives: (1) I think some other reviews mention this, but these have a tendency to ride down in the back, not sure if it should be longer in the back or elastic tighter, but I have to hike these up and (2) they are very long, I am short (5' 3") and they are about four inches too long (i.e., I tried wearing them with 3 inch heels and they were still getting walked on), so I had to hem them in order to wear them (especially because I wanted to wear them with flats.

I really, REALLY wish HUE would realize there's an overlooked demographic of 40+ yr olds out here who would LOVE to wear these potentially best-ever comfy jeggings too.

While these particular jeggings are improved over their past styles, they still have much needed improvements to go.

I am 40-something, 5'7" and about 145/150 lbs. In other words, I'm your average 40-something American female. I ordered a size L.

Pros:
- fabric is great! nice and stretchy, but bounces back and retains shape.
- bootcut. not many, if ANYone, looks good in today's "skinny" jean look. so kudos to HUE for keeping at least one bootcut style around.
- rear pockets are placed perfectly.

Cons:
- The rise is still not high enough, ESPECIALLY in the rear! They may be OK to stand in, but the second I sat down, my entire bum was exposed! If these were just a 1/2" higher in the front, and 2" to 3" higher in the back, we'd be in business.
- As-is, the length is OK. But I have a feeling they'd shrink up when washed. I'd like the length 1" to 1/2" longer. Or offer "Tall".

The only other "complaint" I have is that the rinse is way too dark. I'd like a rinse that looks like worn denim (not too dark and not too light, but blue...not almost black).

Love these leggings; the material is far superior to others I have purchased . However these are not really made for curvy women. The leg and thigh fit great, but the butt and waist are far too large. Will return for a medium size and see how that fits. I wear an 8 in women's bottoms but the size guide told me to purchase a large. Next time I'll trust my instincts.

I am a 35 year old wife/mother/student. I have been looking for a nice looking, comfortable, trendy pair of jeans. I wanted something that wouldn't give me the dreaded mom jean butt. The pockets on this are closer together so they make my small, flat butt look better. Also, not too low of a waist. The slim legs make me look taller and thinner. To think all these years I avoided pants that would have made me look thinner and taller just because I was afraid they were too tight-looking!  I look ten  pounds lighter when I wear these and the bootcut tends to even out my top heaviness (I'm a busty gal).  My husband really likes these on me as well and thinks they are sexy without looking like I'm going clubbing. I feel like I have successfully found a sexy, practical, comfortable non-mom jean. And I don't feel self-conscious wearing these because I feel so good wearing them.

I really like the color. The midnight rinse is very dark which looks a little dressier. I also ordered these in medium wash since I loved these ones so much. I don't think I'll be buying regular jeans again. Seriously, these are that good. There is now a permant place for these in my wardrobe. Actually, for several of these.

It's larger than I thought it would be b/c I couldn't invision the dimensions given. It's nearly true to color. Not as neon as the picture seems to show, but it *is* a beautiful orange! When you open the top, the inside has two sections. The upper top has a small vertical oval mirror on the left, and a pocket on the right. When you unlatch the tab (velcro strap) the divider folds down so you can section smaller items in the upper/top section. This divider is not supported so I suggest storing items in separate cases/bags or they may fall everywhere. I plan to use the upper space to store my make-up items, and the lower section to hold my hair items. (Brush, blow dryer, hair spray etc.)

Here are the dimensions that I've measured: height 9.5 in., width 13.5 in. at middle/top (it tapers down) and about 12.5 in. at the bottom, and 8 in. in depth.

My only complaint is, there 2 teeny-tiny marks on the front, one on the top above the zipper, and the other on the bottom half, in the middle. Don't misunderstand, most people wouldn't even notice these, but I have a *very* discerning eye so I tend to see imperfections that most don't even notice. Otherwise I would have given the case 5-stars. I'm still very happy with this purchase.

reviewText:
Relatively new to getting fit again after about 15 years of poor habits and a health wake up call. Started in February 2018 power walking (cant run) and have progressed to walking 3 miles in 47-49 minutes, so a decent pace. Started experiencing chafing and discomfort due to my standard cotton underwear. Did a lot of research because I was a bit shocked at the price of underwear for workouts. Ordered a few different pairs from different manufacturers and returned them all except the SAXX Kinetic Boxers. Wore them for four days of straight walking and washing them every day. While I went with the XL size recommendation from the website, at first I was a little worried they would be too loose. Far from itand even seemed to fit bit better after a couple of washings. These shorts have impressed me so much I am ordering six more pair of Kinetic along with a pair of Ultra and a pair of Platinum to see how they might be to replace my daily wear.

PRO: You don't know you are wearing underwear, legs don't ride up, wicking action is excellent.
CON: Not a fan of the SAXX lettering, cost although you can find them somewhat on sale.

I am not a profar from it but I do know I have found exceptional underwear for my workouts, and hopefully day to ay wear.

I got this watch about 2 years ago as a gift and here's what I've thought of it in the past 2 years
Pros:
- Accurate most of the time. I've been able to get accurate paces and locations (usually within 100 feet)
- Plastic makes the watch durable and the band is comfortable as long as it isn't too tight
- Once a signal is acquired, it hardly ever loses signal. I even took it to Yosemite once on some light hiking and it never dropped signal
- Never used it in the night for anything besides a watch, but the night light works fine
- It syncs with Strava through the downloadable Soleus apps on PC and Mac
- When I bought this it was around $50 and it does the basics of what more expensive trackers do
Cons:
- Battery life is decent but after a few months it became very inconsistent. sometimes I would go cycling for an hour and the watch would drop down to one bar and return to two bars a while later. Charging is also wonky sometimes with it taking a few minutes to reach 60% or 70% and another hour to reach 100%
- It has no Bluetooth so you're forced to use the computer app if you every want to upload your data to Strava
- I ran into a door once and the watch took most of the hit, breaking the bottom band off. A bit of superglue fixed it, but it came loose after a few months
- Getting a signal often takes up to 10 minutes so unless you plan all of your runs, you'll end up waiting a while for the watch's signal or possibly miss tracking part of your workout
- Navigating through the watch's functions is sometimes cumbersome and I find that sometimes it takes a considerable amount of force to press the buttons
Overall thought:
For the price I got this for, it's worth it. For the current price of $100, I'd rather look at some other fitness trackers. Something like the Huawei Band 2 Pro also has a HR monitor along with Bluetooth and mobile apps for $30 less
summary: (Almost) 2 year review/thoughts. TL,DR: Great value, works 95% of the time but try not to directly hit the band

reviewText:
The GPS is very accurate. It takes a while to get a signal, but all gps watches are like that. Had to look for the user manual on soleus' web page to learn how to program and use it. It's not that easy to use, but it's a matter of getting used to the watch. Another con is it's pretty big, my wrist is slim and have to buckle the strap almost all the way, but I don't mind. The back is silicon -not metal as i read in another review. The features are ok. I used to use a Garmin watch, and there are some features which I miss from my old garmin: if you program it to auto lap every km, you can't take shorter laps with the lap button while you are running; you have to stop and switch the auto lap off (can't have both at the same run, and i generally run a few  warm up kms and then run short laps) . Also, you can see the pace of the current lap, but not the average pace -at least not in a simple way like the garmin watch. Another feature I miss is the fact that it doesn't vibrate when it reaches the lap distance, so if you are listening to music you might not hear the beep.
Having said that, I like the watch very much, nice design, and it works great. Still cannot beleive I got a GPS watch for only $10
summary: Great GPS watch for the price

I am going to ship it back. It was advertised as full-grain leather, which I assumed was something different (as in: higher quality) than "genuine leather", which - so I understand - are just leather scraps glued together. Maybe I was too optimistic about the quality given the low price - but I am still rubbed the wrong way when the description is unclear or misleading and the customer is asked to figure it out for himself. Maybe there is even a difference between "full-grain leather" and "made with full-grain leather". May it as it be: the belt does not meet my expectations and goes back.

This is a 100% leather belt as opposed to a full grain leather belt (MUCH lower quality and durability, search for "Leather 101" or "Leather 102" for a good explanation, genuine leather represents the leftovers of a hide that has already been used to make the best and second best grades of leather). The picture (which displays a full grain leather belt) is misleading, it does not represent the product I received. The item pictured is clearly full grain leather and the item I received is clearly not (from look AND label). Anyone who rated this as a high quality durable belt either: 1) doesn't know what they're talking about and are used to purchasing belts from low quality retailers or 2) received a different product than I did.

I purchased this during my sixth month of pregnancy (#4) due to severe pelvic and ligament pain, and overall think the belly bandit has helped! The fit was great, the ice pack has been heavenly when my back hurts (or I'm just hot!), and I have found it very comfortable (especially compared to other bands I've tried). I said overall it helped, because there were other treatments I used to help with the pain, including icing, stretching, a different workout, chiropractic care, and a tens unit. My pain only gets bad now if I have been on my feet all day, so I wear the band as a preventative measure now, especially when I am very active or working out. It has been very useful! My only complaint is that it does seem a bit overpriced.
summary: Very helpful for pelvic and ligament pain

reviewText:
UPDATE AT ONE MONTH: Couldn't live without it during this twins pregnancy. I sleep in it, walk in it, wear it all the time. Size large works just fine for me. The velcro is wearing a little, which is a shame, and it's lost a little bit of its shape, but it's still totally worth it. Basically it keeps me from being bedridden because even walking down a hall without it feels painful. I'd recommend it to anyone with a multiple pregnancy.

I am also glad I got the black, since I wear it all the time, I can wear it over black yoga pants or skirts if I want and it doesn't jump out at you. And since I wear it constantly and have to adjust it every bathroom run, sometimes it's easier to just wear it on top. I think it's a little more comfortable over a thin layer of clothing (but it's okay under, too).

Other than a pregnancy pillow, this was my most essential twins pregnancy purchase and kept me moving (and working) longer than I would have otherwise.
--

I can't speak to its longevity, but I can say that as a 28 week person pregnant with twins, this saved my day yesterday and today. I am still working and was finding it difficult to move around, stand up and sit down, lean forward, etc. I was having abdominal pain and my doc suggested a support band. I picked this one on the reviews and had it overnighted and delivered to me at work. I put it on right away and found I was able to do things I haven't done in a month, mostly getting up and down more, walking more, doing stairs felt better, leaning down felt better, and I realized how much pain I had actually been in once I put this on and the pain went away. I mean, I'm still huge and pregnant, but movements don't rock me like they were doing. I can move more.

There's no instructions so I wasn't sure how to wear it. I showed my doc and she said wear it LOW. It doesn't go over your belly, it goes under/below it, and the back part covers part of your butt. (Originally I was wearing it too high before I showed her.)

I read online you shouldn't wear it ALL the time - any belly band - but my perinatologist said as long as I wear it as intended, nice and low, I can wear it as much as I want, even to sleep.

This thing is easy to put on with no crazy straps, it feels soft directly on my skin (it's bamboo!), it didn't stink like chemicals or anything and I was comfortable putting it on immediately...I think it's going to be a huge help. I had no idea what size to get so I got a large but it might be a little too big. I figured size large because its twins and my belly is so big, but I was a size small before the pregnancy so a medium would have probably been okay. It doesn't actually really go OVER your belly so consider that in sizing, it's not so much your belly size but your hips and butt. I am too lazy to try exchanging it so I'll just stick with the large, I think, plus I can't live without it now. A little too big is okay, it just gaps a tiny bit in the back.

I was wearing a dress yesterday - a tight one - and you couldn't see this at all in the front. In the back it simply gave me an extra flat butt because it covers a lot of my butt. Whatever though.

If this just gets me through a few more weeks of work where I can actually be PRODUCTIVE instead of sitting in a chair staring at things I'd like to move but don't want to, it will be worth the money. I wish I'd gotten it a bit earlier.
summary: Day 2 and I am so happy (Updated after a month)

Before the first one arrived, I had wondered if they could double as a dramatic long dress, but they just don't hold that honor.  The material is a satin polyester with just a bit too much shine for sophistication.  That being said, they are a lovely option for home, and every bit so for answering the door to deliveries and such (it doesn't feel like I'm caught in my nightgown).  Additionally, wearing these kaftans at home helps save wear and tear on my going-out clothes I would otherwise wear.  One con is that the fabric likes static (winter time here in Washington state).  A pro is the great price.  Just the amount of yardage used justifies the price.  I took off one star because the sewing quality on the neck on this one wasn't the finest.  I can see a bit of the hemmed fabric peeking out under the gold trim.  Nothing I can't live with for wearing at home.  Overall, I am very pleased.

reviewText:
I don't like it as much as the one I bought in Germany a bit over a decade ago for two reasons. First, while it has two large pockets, they are on opposite sides of the wallet. The one I used to use had a large pocket and small pocket on the same side. Second, the material is a lot thicker and much less rigid than that one, meaning it's more prone to bending and folding and takes up much more space at the same time.

The one benefit is the single belt loop style, which is less difficult to use than the double belt loop for the one I had in Germany. However, that's also a drawback, as it means this thing hangs lower and is more prone to getting bent when you sit down, vs. the other one which had two belt loops on the long side, so it sat closer to your waist and was less like to get bent. Unfortunately the belt loops on my old one eventually came undone, so I got this one rather than spend time trying to resew them on. But after using this for a bit, I think trying to resew them might be wort the trouble.

I love these shoes.  I've had them for about a year, now.  Patent leather is awesome - scuffs just wipe right off with your hand.  (Not like vinyl patent, where scuffs are permanent.)  If you've never worn real patent leather, you're in for a treat as to how durable and snazzy looking these are.  I get compliments on them all the time.  These are fairly comfortable - didn't need a lot of break in time.  I have walked several blocks in them over lunch and been fine (I am over weight, and comfortable shoes can be a problem).  I would not want to "shop till you drop" in them,  I gave them 4 stars because my feet sweat a little in them, and I have slightly damp socks when I take them off.  This has not been a major issue for me - and I may have them on for 10 hours at a time.  I do not wear them several days in a row.  I have a "C" width foot, and the wide is ok - maybe a tad on the snug side.  If you wear a true "B" width - I think medium will be OK.  But, if you really have a "C" width foot, get the wide.  The length runs true to size compared to other Clarks shoes.

These socks suck. First, each pair is individually wrapped and hang-tagged for display at a store, so you have to undo EACH pair. Secondly, the quality is just bad. Every time the color changes from one shade to another, there's a loose tail of thread on the inside, sometimes nearly 2 inches long! In some cases they get looped back into the material and form a loop that your toes will get caught in. There's a reason they're "no show" - they barely reach the top of my heel. I got the size 9-11, and I wear a 10. If I wore an 11, I doubt they would fit at all. Lastly, the material is so thin that you can feel all the little rubber dots on the bottom. It's like walking on gravel. "Luxury" - no way.
summary: Made in China - and it shows

reviewText: It is a nice watch and it keeps pretty good time a mechanical watch. I would recommend this watch for someone who wants a mechanical watch.

This is a gorgeous black and gold mens watch. Its an automatic mechanical watch with a style that is somehow both elegant and perhaps slightly fussy with a baroque and steampunk look to it. Its an automatic mechanical watch which means that it does not use a battery.

The front face is lovely. It is a fairly thick plain gold bezel with a slightly convex glass behind which you have a beautifully detailed black and gold face which incorporates many small details. The large clock face surrounds three additional miniature dials that denote the date, day of the week and 24 hours. The main clock face is easy to read with large roman numerals. Oddly 3, 6 and 9 are missing but you don't really notice because the inset border that surrounds the miniature dials tapers towards those points defining those unlabeled hours well enough.

The hands are of medium thickness tapering at both ends in an elongated kite shape. There is a seconds hand which is a needle with a small disk at the pointing end. The hands are inset with some luminous material that glows green in the dark. The seconds hand has only the disk glow while the other hands glow along the whole length.

The crown is golden and nicely knurled with a golden slab on each side. When pushed in, the crown can be used to wind the mechanism. Pulled out, you set the time. Meanwhile the gold slabs at each side are actually mechanical buttons which with each click moves either the date or the day along one position. It works very well and is simple to use.

Automatic mechanical movement

As I mentioned, this is not a battery operated watch. It uses a mechanical winding mechanism. It you turn the watch over, the back plate has a large glass window inset behind which you can see the mechanism. A large half circle center mounted pendulum rocks back and forth when the watch moves. The movement winds the watch. Behind the pendulum you can see some of the inner workings, wheels and cogs rotating and rocking back and forth. Its quite fascinating and very cool.

Other than that you have a black leather strap with white stitching and a simple gold buckle. Its an attractive watch that looks good with almost anything thanks to the black and gold combination. But it looks especially nice peeking out from behind a cuff of a shirt and dark blazer.

In Use

The watch works wonderfully but you do need good eyesight to read the miniature dials for date, day and 24 hours. The detail on the face is great but my husband for whom I got this watch for needs good light (preferably daylight) in order to read them. The main clock face is easy to read which is the main thing.

The instructions state to wind the watch twice a day. My husband found that so long as you wear it and are fairly active you only have to wind it at night before going to bed. The automatic winding through the weighted pendulum that uses your movement works well enough. Pitching it about 20 or so degrees a couple of times is enough to get the mechanism started from stopped. So if you are active it keeps itself wound up quite well. Having said that, you can always wind the crown at any time for insurance. If you forget to wind it before you put it away for the night it will have stopped by the morning and will need the time set again.

Conclusion

Its a lovely inexpensive watch and my husband really likes it. It is a medium size but still qute thick. He noticed the strap is not as big as some, he has reasonably wide wrists of about 7.5 inches and there is only just enough strap to fit a 8 inch wrist and still capture the pointed end of the strap in the loop.

Its a really nice watch that comes in a nice flat dark bronze display box. Its not too heavy and looks really nice. We both like it.

Disclaimer: I received this watch in exchange for an honest and fair review.  The opinions expressed are my own.
Returned.  Arrived broken.  Not good was a gift.

Some of the metalwork is not as precisely molded as one would hope, but it is not noticeable unless you look very closely at it.  When wound regularly, the watch keeps perfect time.  The leather band could be of higher quality, but I will replace it with a better one when this one wears out.

We are tough on watches in this house, and we have a gorgeous $800 watch that cannot be worn because there are no replacement bands in existence.  That band on broke repeatedly and can no longer be repaired - which is why I chose an inexpensive watch with a easily replaceable band.

reviewText:
Size is adjustable, via Velcro strips on the headband.  The crown of the headband is also slightly adjustable - tightening or loosening the crown adjusts the depth of crown.  I've replaced the string crown adjustment with a leather thong.
  I rate the over-all production values as very high.  The faux leather chinstrap seems durable enough.  The canvas exterior seems durable, readily cleanable, porous enough to soak the pith, but tight enough that the helmet doesn't drip even when well soaked, and well stitched.  Rivets are solidly applied, as is the metal crown vent.  The waterproof canvas interior is glued to the pith (no data as yet as to how well the glue holds up) and stitched  under the canvas brim.
  I researched he market looking for a pith helmet.  An official British Army helmet runs hundreds of dollars.  There is a wide variety of reproduction helmets, mostly of various British uniforms.  I like the look of this style, it  reminds me of Life Guards when I was a kid.
  Functionally, the he provides excellent shade for the head, eyes, ears, and neck, yet is light and stable under a high wind.  The chin strap may never be used.  When properly fitted, the headband provides a layer of air between the head and the helmet.  If the helmet gets soaked (outside only - plug all holes and submerge to the brim [caution, the fully soaked pith may be soft and subject to deformation]) the process of evaporation cools the helmet, and hence the head.  This works  very well for me walking and working in the desert.  I suspect this helmet is also excellent rain gear, but I may never find out.

This was not an inexpensive helmet compared to others but the quality and attention to detail is very poor. The string that holds the suspension broke the first time I wore. The sewn material that the string goes through came unsewn the second time I wore it. I regret this purchase.

A nice quality little pocket watch, I thought it was going to be a bit cheap-looking because of the price, but it isn't at all!
I love it and others seem to enjoy it as well, and the mechanism works perfectly.

This watch overall is ok if you know how to use it. It is though very glitchy and complicated, I still haven't fully figured out how to use this! So first of all, when you try to tap the screen to turn it on, it doesn't work, you have to literally SLAP the watch just to get it to show to time. Setting the time was a pain too. In order to set the time:

1. Press and hold on the text "LED" at the bottom middle of the screen.
2. Set the hour by tapping the bottom middle on the watch's screen until it reaches the hour of your desire.
3. Press and hold on the text "LED" again to proceed to entering the minutes place on the watch. Same setting process as #2
4. Press and hold again to reach the option for setting the year, tap to change year.
5. Press and hold to get to the option for changing the month, and press and hold again to get to the option to set the day.
6. Press and hold again to finish and fully setup the watch!

After the pain of setting the watch, it is a pain to get the watch to show the time, because it has the worst capacitive touchscreen ever! I would not recommend buying this unless you are looking for a really cheap barely functioning watch to give to your worst enemy!

reviewText: I was looking for Japanese Chin items to add to my Mother's Christmas gift and this was just the little thing I needed.

I purchased this case for Canon G15, and they fit great. Some reviewers indicate that the shell of the case is not actually rigidly hard. It's totally fine because it actually provide another form or protection for a camera inside. I dropped this once with the camera from around 2 feet. I can't find a scratch, and the camera is well protected. I highly recommend this for any camera that has a size comparable to Canon G15. To see more photos how Canon G15 fit in this case, you may check out the pictures I just uploaded.

Overall quality of the case is good and it is well constructed. It is not a hard case. The outer surface areas are a firm spongy material adding some additional padding. However, it doesn't fit my new Nikon Coolpix P7700. I can't give the product a bad review because it is a generic case, and the P7700 is a new camera and there isn't much to research yet on cases.

I bought this case specifically for my P7700. If I leave the strap off, and force it, I can get it to in the case. Forget the stock lens cap staying on it. But it is a struggle to get the case zipped up. This is NOT a good fit for this camera.
Smaller Point & Shoot cameras it will work well for, and you will have a little extra room for a spare battery, memory card, cable etc.
On Case Logic's website this case is known as: Pro Point and Shoot Camera Case EHC-102-BLACK
SInce the P7700 has a long lens and larger than average body for a Point & Shoot camera, a compact camcorder case should be a better fit. I am going to order: Compact Camcorder Case EHC-103-BLACK
http://www.amazon.com/Case-Logic-EHC-103-Compact-Camcorder/dp/B005X64OT4/ref=sr_1_1?s=electronics&ie=UTF8&qid=1353720248&sr=1-1&keywords=Compact+Camcorder+Case+EHC-103-BLACK
summary: Nikon P7700 camera NOT a good fit for this case

reviewText: I have looked all over for tube socks - a throwback to the "old days."  I used to snicker at my mom (and now I'm sorry) because she would walk in a store to buy socks and start explaining to the salesperson how the socks she wore would eventually start rubbing against all five toes because of the bulky seam across the toes.  Well . . . paybacks are heck, as now I have the same problem.  I'm going to purchase more of these socks.  They are comfortable and fit well.  The heels on my "fitted" socks always ended up above my heel since I wear a size 6-1/2 shoe - the socks were always just a smidge too large.  No sock really hugged my heel.  Well . . . tube socks don't have heels, so there you are.  No problem.  No heels, no seam across the toes - it doesn't get any better.  Thanks!!

I will probably end up wearing a corset underneath as a shaper, as there is no boning in the costume - strips of gold lace on the front imitate the look of boning, but are not. The ruching and off-the-shoulder design elements are very flattering for us fuller figured gals, and the fringe accents just the right places without being too much decoration. The bra section can be adjusted as to how much cleavage one wants to show, which is always a good thing. The disappointing parts were the accessories - the "hat" is a collapsible ring with fabric stretched over it, and the "choker" is a ribbon with a very fake-looking jewel pinned on it. reviewText:
I've been wearing Injinji toe socks for over a year and they are the only running sock for me. After dislocating a couple of toes I found that not even taping before a run would prevent those tootsies from blistering. I did a lot of online research and out of pure desperation I purchased a pair of Injinji socks. Happily I have not had another toe blister since that very first "toe sock run"

These mid weight trail socks are perfect for my early morning fall and winter runs. I love that extra thickness and cushioning. But keep in mind that if your shoes fit like a glove these socks will be bulky. Not a problem for me as my runners are wide in the toe box so that there's plenty of room for toe splay. Although it may feel a bit weird when you first put on these socks, by the time you tie your shoes and head out for your run all "weirdness" is gone.

These socks fit true to size. Follow the wash instructions and your Injinji socks will give you miles and miles of comfortable rides.

So I contacted Fownes after trying to buy them elsewhere, to try to buy them directly from the manufacturer, as the non-Amazon retailers I found on the web that I trust (Nordstrom's, Dillard's) didn't have the color or size I needed online, and I am 55 miles from the nearest one. Fownes directed me back to those retailers and to Amazon. All of the Amazon links Fownes sent were for QuantityBuy. I wrote back, naming this Amazon seller (FursNewYork QuantityBuy) specifically to make sure, and Fownes assured me they are a "verified, authorized" dealer for them. QuantityBuy shipped them immediately and the gloves arrived very quickly. They are genuine leather, soft cashmere inside and beautiful. Very happy!

Costume is as appears.  Spandex & comfortable.  Covers from neck to toes - gloves, boots, sash are all attached. This presented me with a slight problem - I am 5'10", 180 lbs - so the costume (I ordered XXL) was a little short overall for me. This made the costume fit a little odd in places - little too low in crotch, tight across shoulders.  I also agree with another review I read - it makes shoes a tricky situation.  It's hard to fit shoes inside the costume - I found even socks a tight fit.  I bought the costume to wear to a mud run with obstacles however, so I made some modifications before I used it.  I ended up cutting slits in the feet so I could slide my toes through - I wore tennis shoes over the feet.  I also cut the hand portion of the gloves off (I knew I would be climbing many things in the mud - wanted traction!).  The costume was warm - a plus in November when you are wet and muddy.  And it survived beautifully.  I was able to rinse off the majority of the mud with the portable showers they had at the race.  I didn't see any visible holes, etc - and I was crawling through some nasty mud.  And overall I came out of the race fairly unscathed - so worked great for me.  Just keep the length in mind if you are tall.

reviewText: We needed a couple realistic (plastic) durable swords for a "battle" on board a float in our community parade (adults doing the battle), and we needed it fast (ie. Amazon Prime).  So we took a chance on these even though there were no reviews.  They are incredible props!... but with one hitch.  The handle is lose, and one came apart when we were practicing the battle scene, so we broke the other one apart (i.e. pulled out the handle and broke the two 1/8" plastic pins holding it).  Then we riveted through the same holes.  You could also go to your hardware store and just use 2 screws (#10 x 3/4" should do it).  They were spectacular!!  We would have given it 5 stars if not for this fix, and to be honest the fix probably wouldn't be necessary unless your usage involved some abuse like ours.

reviewText: Great Looking mask!! You just have to be careful you don't drop it.... I got it from my son I've had to glue it back together four times....

This is a fine, resin replica of the mask from the Jim Carrey film, "The Mask", which is shipped over from China, so you have to wait at least a couple weeks for it, sometimes more. Mine was projected to arrive after October 31st, I believe (and I think I ordered it in early October), but it in fact arrived before then, so not too bad. The sculpture is great, but here was the big problem for me...

This mask comes with an adjustable strap, as if it was meant to be worn as a mask. I am not sure why they would do that, since anyone ordering this is wanting it as a film prop replica, and it makes no sense to wear it. In the film, when this mask is put on the face, it is merged with the face and becomes something different entirely. Wearing this mask as it is makes no sense. Someone buying this is going to hang it on the wall, or carry it around, or in my case, I used it as an aquarium decoration. It is lifesize and looks awesome in my aquarium, but the problem of the straps is removing them. They are attached with metal pieces that are a brutal exercise to remove, even with wire cutters like I used. In the process, I actually broke off a good sized part of one side of the mask! On the bright side, superglue reattached it like new, and with its grain replica design, there's no way you can tell. On the downside, there are holes in each side where the metal pieces for the straps were. Small, but if you look right at 'em, you won't miss 'em. I suppose they can be filled in with something. I'll have to do that soon.

The other thing is that, while it is impressive looking and the metal-looking piece in the middle (the nose piece) is beautifully painted to look like real metal, the rest of the mask is a solid, dark brown color. I ended up giving it streaks of a light green wash with acrylic paint, and it came out pretty good. So, basically, if you order this mask, expect some more work to do on it. Have superglue on handy, and go to the hobby store and get a tube of light green, acrylic paint, or as I used, mix some blue and yellow. Also, have some wire cutters and superglue on hand. And, don't try to put a green wash over the metal area. It looks better without it. I'm going to have to repaint that area myself, unfortunately, but the only reason I tried the green wash there was because some of the metal paint chipped off at some point. Maybe it was too thin and flaked off in the fish tank. However, I got some paint to redo it and will take care of that soon. Yeah, it sounds like a lot of work, but it looks amazing when you remove the straps and tweak it with some painting, so it is definitely worthwhile, and this was one of the cheaper versions I was able to find.

reviewText: Thin, small fit but wearable as a layer under something else.

This is an East Asian sizing top, which means in my case, normally an M/ PM size in the US would be an L, if not XL, there.  ( I am 5 feet 3, 128 lbs.). So if you are larger than me, chances are you won't find a size of this top for you, or in many other clothes in places like Japan or Hong Kong.
The good:  it is about the only nursing turtle neck top that I can find in the US.  I tried milk nursing wear, figure8maternity, local retail stores like motherhood, boob design....etc.  There is just NO nursing turtle neck that I can layer under my regular sweaters, you know, just a loose fit/ bat wings sleeves but way better quality real wool sweaters, such as Ann Taylor.  I am so glad I fit into its largest size.  ( now if only one of the others offer a good nursing turtle neck, my review would be different.  Also, I am willing to pay even more for a good one but alas.....)
The bad:  totally agree with another reviewer on that there is way too many things happening under the "hood".  They design in strange straps and pads there, and I just removed the pads and other stuffs.  Also, there is a chemical smell right out of the bag.  Although it disappears after wash.  I suspect it is the thin polyurethane strip used to finish the inner layer, which in my opinion, totally unnecessary.  They should just save all the trouble on the pads and straps, and use the cost to do a decent finish for the inner layer.  After all, it is the part that's closest to the baby when nursing.
summary: A tight fit but serve its purpose-- keep me warm

I worked in the woods for about five years as a timberfaller in western Washington. I started out using two inch suspenders that would support the use of a shoulder pad for easing the burden of carrying my saw on a long walk in to my strip. I tired of that and switched to a belt and let my shoulder suffer choosing, rather, to have a belt that would support my wedges and a scabbard for a small falling axe.

Now, years later, I no longer work in the woods and I am no longer a trim chap and to ease the hip pain from having to tighten my belt up to the max just to hold my pants up, I've once again switched to suspenders. I bought a pair of these Filson (long) suspenders, they are cadillacs, one and half inch suspenders that are made of tough materials. Probably too good and pretty expensive for the likes of me. I am going to test out some other brands and if they are similar (and less expensive) I will most likely switch my buying preferences in that direction. These Filsons are great. In the woods, as in most of life, some of the best things are merely tradition, tradition, tradition. While these might be overkill and very dressy, they are not solely the realm of starched shirt foresters, but, sure, they can wear them too.

The leather button-ends of these suspenders are high quality and very stiff and, therefore, very difficult to button (or unbutton, which is the point of a good set of wood's suspenders).

I'll rework a statement that an old woodsman told me about surmounting the difficulty of making choker cables cooperate with what you want them to do, in regard to the difficulty that some have in buttoning the leather button-ends that these suspenders have . . . "Boy, you've just got to be a little smarter than the leather."

Update: I have been wearing these suspenders daily and, while they still fit my 6'3" frame, they seem to have less adjustability today then they did originally, so they seem to be shrinking over time. They have not been washed or dried and are rarely rain saturated, but nevertheless . . .

I still think that these are worth the 5 star rating.

reviewText:
**Please read addendum first***
I was skeptical about this top (Especially when I took it out of the package and could see daylight through both layers of fabric).  However, my husband assured me that he can't see skin (although I will have to be sure and wear a dark bra) and I didn't buy it to be a toasty warm sweater....just the opposite.  I get so hot when we visit certain homes during the winter because they've got their heat cranked so far up, it's hard to breathe!  I need something that looks nice but is lightweight.  This is perfect!  The ribbed hem keeps it from being too stretchy at the bottom and the ribbed cuffs make the sleeves just snug enough that you can push them up and they stay but are not too tight.  The fabric is lightweight and soft without being too flimsy and clingy.  The neck is not tight but is a little high.  I suppose you could just roll it twice if ot bothered you.  It's absolutely true to size!  I'm 5'8" and 240lbs.  I usually wear a size 24/26 top (with a generous D cup and big ol' back porch) and I ordered a 1X.  It fits perfectly with just enough blousiness (hope that's a word) that it doesn't feel snug.  Very comfortable.  I have to say, it's definitely not an expensive looking shirt but it doesn't look like it came off the Walmart clearance rack, either.  It's just a good shirt to put on when you want to look nice but you're going to grandma's where it's going to be 95 degrees inside!
****Addendum to original post: I just looked at this product again and it has doubled in price since I bought it TWO DAYS AGO!  I'm telling you, ladies, it was barely worth $27!!!!  It's definitely not worth $50!!!  How ridiculous!  I'm knocking off two stars.  This company should be ashamed of themselves!

There are two problems with this scarf, which I ordered in eggplant.

First, it is advertised as "100% Pashmina" which is a straight up lie. When the product arrived, it doesn't look or feel like pashmina (which is a type of soft goats wool, as well as a style) at all. It is more similar to viscose, which is made from bamboo. If they mean pashmina style (which it is), DROP THE 100%, as that is entirely misleading.

Second, I don't think this is even real real viscose! I own a number of pashmina-style viscose scarves, and they are butter soft after being washed and nice and light for summer. This scarf, however, is still scratchy after more than a dozen washes, which makes it most likely acrylic. It looks like viscose, but feels like scratchy cheap plastic.

I can't speak for the other colors, but in the eggplant (purple), this item is worth about $3 tops. It's scratchy, doesn't breathe, and doesn't drape correctly.

NOT RECOMMENDED.

It gets 2 stars instead of 1 because it at least *looks* like the picture. It only gets 2 because of straight up false advertising and lies.
summary: Viscose, and poor quality at that

reviewText: The scarf is very pretty and soft. I actually purchased it to use as a sarong and it fits the bill... it's not wool and is very light and thin. I like it for the purpose I bought it but if it holds up I will sue it as a regular scarf during the fall.

I bought the turquoise wrap a few weeks ago and was delighted when I pulled it out of the bag. The color was vibrant and the size and heft were just right--light but just right for using as a scarf and not necessarily a shawl.  But then I noticed the tag: it was way too far away from a corner and the adhesive was fierce: 2 thin strips of tape that fastened the folded-behind ends of the tag to the fabric.  This tag was also a laundry guide, stated the product was made in China and identified the fabric as "70% pashmina 30% silk." I honestly don't know if there's any pashmina (wool) or silk in it but that doesn't bother me...rayon or viscose is fine as long as the wrap is pretty and has no bad smell.  Unless of course I can't remove the adhesive or there are any runs in the fabric. The turquoise had both problems. So I contacted the company and explained the problem and asked for my money back. Happily, their answer was yes. I asked if they wanted me to return the wrap? No, just send us a picture: fine, even if they're verifying my honesty, as long as they're not making me return it, I don't mind.  So I emailed them a couple pics and they refunded my purchase in full (no shipping charged in the first place, another bonus). As I told them, I might be able to wear it but would have to take pains to cover up the adhesive and make sure it doesn't stick to itself. There is also the run to look out for.

I told the company that in appreciation for the refund, I'd buy another scarf. I cruised up and down the colors because the price varies a few dollars. I chose this "fuschsia" (yes, I'm cheap...and I'm like a magpie with bright colors!) and just got it today. The tag is a little different: doesn't have the laundry instructions or country made, and the adhesive is a glue that covers the whole back of the tag instead of 2 strips. Jeez...I just tried to carefully pry the tag off and it pulled threads way out of shape. I know enough about woven things that you can often ease threads back properly if you gently tug a handful of fabric from both directions. That did help a bit but from either side of the scarf you can make out where the tag was.  There are also 2 small runs in this wrap but they're no biggie. You should know that this fabric snags easily.

So for nice size and color, and good customer service, I give it 5 stars. For the annoying tags and runs, I give it 2 stars. This averages to 3 1/2 stars which I bump up to 4 because you can't beat this price.

So I cautiously recommend this scarf. Only if you want to use it exclusively as a shawl or for a formal occasion will it not work. (And shame on you if you'd pay so little for such a visible accessory for a wedding or whatever.)
summary: The turquoise and fuschsia [sic]... they merit 3 1/2 stars so I rounded it up to 4

I have a self professed bag problem. As such I am constantly seeking the "perfect bag". I have an eBag Mobile office that I really like so when I so this carry-on I knew I had found a great bag. This bag is a very high quality. Zippers are very sturdy and have interlocking feature that allows for secure locking during travel. It has several different zippered areas for all your travel needs. The handle has several different height options which is unique and helpful and the wheels roll well. I really appreciate that the back side of this bag is a durable solid material that is meant to stand up to a lot of impact. even though I have not purchased this at Amazon but directly from ebags, I want to warn people that indeed the handle is a pain in the butt, as stated by another customer.  It seems flimsy, and it comes out all the way when you pull it out the first time, then you have to push it back in and lock it into a lower position.  Whoever thought of designing this like so must not travel much...
LOVE, LOVE, LOVE this bag!  So roomy!  Will use as carry-on for a cruise.  Very happy with my purchase!

This suitcase is awesome!!!  I traveled for 2 weeks across southern England and Paris and only used this suitcase and the eBags Mother Load backpack. I was looking for something that made the best use of space and could fit a much as possible.  It is very well designed and using any of the outer compartments/pockets or the mesh pocket on the inside did not take away from the size of the main compartment by pushing into it.  I used the eBag travel cubes to keep my clothes organized, which helped a lot to keep everything from getting wrinkled  and made a great use of the small space.  It expands well to add lots of extra room.  I did check it at the airport, so can't comment on how it does getting into overheads.

One of the main things I was most impressed with this suitcase was the design was perfect and it did not once tip over when being wheeled around or standing upright despite me attaching my very heavy eBags mother load backpack to the collapsible handle and an additional regular backpack.  Despite me cramming it (probably) too full and attaching additional bags to it, it wheeled smoothly across level floors and was not too difficult to wheel around London and the cobblestone sidewalks we had to use to get to the underground.  I felt a bit sorry for my travel companions and the amount of trouble they had with the small wheels on their luggage and for how often they tipped over.

I'd recommend this bag to anyone!  It was perfect for my needs, it makes great use of space, the zippers are very strong, it expands well, and fits a ton.  On the eBags website there is a video where they go over all the features of the suitcase which I found very helpful in deciding to purchase this bag.

Overall, this is a really nice bag. One thing that could be improved upon is the inside mesh zipper compartment that is on the inside of the front flap opening. The zipper begins its opening at the bottom where the opening flap hooks to the inside bag. If you open the suitcase & just want to get something out of the meshed zipped area you have to open the flap all the way and lay it flat or everything in the mesh area will fall out. The zipper should be at the top so you can just open the suitcase, lift the flap and unzip & reach your hand down into the meshed area. Every time I use this suitcase I think what a stupid design. Other than that it is nice, but if I had known it was designed like that before buying it I would not have.
summary: Inside Mesh Area Could Be Better

Perfectly sized carry on (as long as you don't expand it).
